I'm currently running a ZeroNet proxy, but I have a problem with how it handles big files.
&nbsp;
At the moment, every time a user clicks on a video file that isn't being actively seeded by the proxy, it will automatically start downloading the file into the hard drive of the proxy server.
&nbsp;
That means that, given a sufficient amount of time and sufficient amount of users, the hard drive will eventually be overloaded. This will discourage ZeroNet proxies from hosting zites that have big files on them. 
&nbsp;
Even with the 'help share and distribute big files' option disabled, you're still forced to download and seed the videos/files to your hard drive, every time you click on one. It doesn't allow you to simply stream the videos/files from the currently active peers/seeders.
&nbsp;
I'm starting to believe that this is the reason why Proxies have been vanishing. Proxies are a great way to introduce people to ZeroNet.

