Looks like this is gonna be my favourite reddit for a while.. ^^
&nbsp;
Can't believe I'm gonna be 25 this year. I presume a lot of us would have ditched our primary school dreams of going to Mars by now. After all, how will governments ever scrape up enough money for a Mars colony, when there's autonomous drones, tanks and bombs yet to be hauled through the middle east? Surely we can settle for a more realistic sort of milestone for mankind .. such as eradicating wealth inequality. 
&nbsp;
.. But by the looks of it, most of us have already given up on that one as well.
&nbsp;
I'm not one of those people. Think about it - we've had the enlightenment, the industrial revolution. People used to starve to death back in the old days, but nowadays obesity is more of a problem, even in third world countries. 
&nbsp;
A UBI would no doubt be the first step towards building a world in which our biggest worry will literally be, not knowing what to do with our spare time. Our precarious, globalized, debt-based economy is no longer working for us. The vast majority of us are already living on 'non-existent money'.. except, you'll be re-paying the elite for as long as you live, unless you're privileged enough to be part of this upper class.
&nbsp;
The great thing about using cryptocurrencies to make this dream come a reality, as opposed to relying on governments, is that it puts power directly in the hands of the people. You've probably already heard about Venezuela - the infamous socialist trainwreck. That's actually where I used to live..
&nbsp;
My dad also used to be a diplomat, and once had a gig working as a translator for Putin and Chavez. Back in 2009, me and my mum went on holiday to Russia. Dad took me on a tour through the Venezuelan embassy in Moscow.
&nbsp;
One thing that struck me the most about the people who worked there, was just how materialistic they all seemed. Dad used to take out cash from out of his wallet while we were at the petrol stations and wave it around before getting into his Range rover. He claims to be a socialist, but ironically enough, the only reason he decided to work as a diplomat in the first place, was so that he could live the life of a rockstar. Fancy suits, drinks, prostitutes... 
&nbsp;
I should add, he no longer works at the embassies anymore, he's unemployed. Venezuela was a failed experiment, no doubt, but to think that the blame lies within the 'generosity' of a government who only wanted to help its struggling working class, is a big mistake. Just because a government claims to be 'for the people', doesn't mean they have to keep their promises. If you wanna get rich in Venezuela, work for the government.
&nbsp;
..anywhoo, we probably need our own CryptoUBI talk here on ZeroNet, although we still seem to be a very small community. Let's do something awesome. Pessimism is a waste of time. I should add, I'm an optimistic pessimist. I'm pretty sure I think the world sucks, but I'm also pretty sure we can fix that.

