Not so long ago, I'd actually received a call on my smartphone... New Zealand number, apparently... from a lady telling me that I had expressed interest in 'trading and investments' with their company.
&nbsp;
Knowing that it was a scam, I hung up the phone at the time .. and yet, the phone calls persisted. 
&nbsp;
Me and my friend came up with an idea; we would get her to visit a fake blog that I created. The fake blog was hosted on a Nginx webserver, and was running a cryptocurreny miner at 100% speed and CPU usage. We were just fucking around though.. nothing serious..
&nbsp;
Didn't take long for us to convince the lady on the phone to click on our link. The Nginx access log revealed her IP. It turned out, the call originated from the Philippines, not New Zealand. She had a slightly American accent .. and was pretty fluent at it .. I presume she studied English in her home country with the help of an American teacher.
&nbsp;
..fast forward into December 2017.. I've now become the target of almost non-stop calls. I've had to install Call Blocker on my phone, but even that hasn't helped; the scammers are known to use number spoofers. I've had calls originating from London, Texas, Australia.. New Zealand.. everywhere in the world. I've had callers with numbers like +000000 ... or even just '1'.
&nbsp;
It's as if they were all reading from a script. I would get men, women from all around the world asking me to make a $250 deposit and start 'betting' on rising and falling prices of stocks / assets / etc. They'd take you to a webpage that looks something like the LCD screens on Wall Street.
&nbsp;
After doing a bit of research on the matter, it turns out that this Binary Options trend is relatively new and has actually become quite a popular 'online investment game' ... which has practically filled the void left over by the crackdown on online gambling. This isn't your typical 'nigerian scam' ... these aren't poor people in Africa trying to make a quick buck, it's a multi-million dollar business, and even intelligent people are falling for it. Lawyers, doctors .. elderly people on a pension .. you name it. 
&nbsp;
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RFH-c-PwQ5M
&nbsp;
The way it works is.. when you sign up with them, you're basically agreeing to taking a risk. They'll tell you that you're gonna make a lot of money, sure. But the Terms and Conditions they get you to agree on still indicate the Risk factor, and it's this risk factor they take advantage of in order to get away with their ill-gotten gains. So you're practically gambling, not investing.. and the odds are purposely rigged so that these websites can profit and walk away with your money.. and there's absolutely nothing authorities can do about it because it's overseas. Chances are, a lot of these trades and stock prices are random numbers, and aren't real.

