I believe this could also be a barrier to having more ZeroNet mobile users, because mobile users usually have limited storage.. and it would be quite a hassle having to delete every single video after you watch it. 
&nbsp;
It's interesting. Unlike ZeroNet big files, the way WebTorrent worked is that, every time you loaded / streamed a torrent.. **the file was stored in your RAM memory**. You could then choose whether you wanted to load it onto your hard drive.
&nbsp;
In effect, anyone who watched a video automatically became a seeder, even if they didn't have the client installed. If you closed the tab, you stopped seeding; the file is automatically unloaded from the RAM.
&nbsp;
I suppose the short term solution would be for big-file sites like ZeroUp and KopyKate to enable optional WebTorrent support. You could enable 'seeding to WebRTC peers' as you watch a video/download a file.. though it would be far better if it all belonged to the same network.. otherwise you'd have two sets of peers for two different networks.

